-- Hong Kong shares close down on weakness in financials, property
-- 
-- Mon Dec 15, 2014 03:10AM EST
-- None



HONG KONG, Dec 15 (Reuters) - Hong Kong shares finished down on Monday despite a late afternoon rally on mainland indexes, as Hong Kong investors sold off China-related financials and real estate names.

The Hang Seng index <.HSI> fell 1.0 percent, to 23,027.85, while the China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> lost 0.2 percent, to 11,212.65 points.Among the most actively traded stocks on Hong Kong's main board were CCT Land <0261.HK>, up 5.9 percent to HK$0.02,  Wai Yuen Tong Medicine Holdings <0897.HK>, down 15.6 percent to HK$0.10 and Renhe Commercial Holdings <2904.HK>, unchanged at HK$0.03. Chinese investment flowing from Shanghai into Hong Kong through the mutual market access pilot programme remained tepid, taking up only 0.2 billion yuan of the 10.5 billion yuan daily quota <.SQUOTA.HS>. Total trading volume of companies included in the the HSI index was 1.7 billion shares.(Editing by Richard Borsuk)  Keywords: MARKETS HONGKONG STOCKS/CLOSE